{"type":"message","id":"4f1690ae","parentId":"2b122629","timestamp":"2026-03-23T03:34:47.161Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"I can see the Telegram config. It's currently using polling (`dmPolicy: \"pairing\"`). For webhooks, I need a public URL that Telegram can call to send updates. \n\nLooking at the gateway config:\n- `gateway.mode: \"local\"` \n- `gateway.bind: \"loopback\"` — this means it's only listening locally\n\nFor webhooks, Telegram needs a public HTTPS URL to send updates to. Since the gateway is on loopback only, I'd need to either:\n1. Set up a tunnel (like ngrok or cloudflare tunnel) to expose the gateway publicly\n2. Or use Telegram's \"local webhook\" mode if OpenClaw supports that\n\n\n3. The `gateway.remoteUrl` setting might be the key here — if I set that to a public URL, Telegram could reach the gateway through it. Though I'm realizing this Windows machine likely doesn't have a public IP, so I'd definitely need a tunnel solution to make webhooks work. and this is a consumer internet connection, so there's no public IP or domain. For webhooks to work, I'd need to either set up a reverse tunnel with something like ngrok or Cloudflare Tunnel pointing to port 18789, or use a service like ngrok's TCP tunnel.\n\nLet me check the Telegram plugin documentation to understand how OpenClaw actually implements webhooks and what configuration options are available.","thinkingSignature":"40c671fc1a4a8740f283e27287dda9839efa6cc5ed4c334554dcebace03cecca"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_ggkjzdvd3mnb_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"openclaw plugins telegram --help 2>&1"}},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_ggkjzdvd3mnb_2","name":"read","arguments":{"path":"C:\\Users\\Zwmar\\AppData\\Roaming\\npm\\node_modules\\openclaw\\extensions\\stock\\telegram\\index.ts","limit":100}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":20117,"output":367,"cacheRead":12