{"type":"message","id":"fd11a575","parentId":"ac23221e","timestamp":"2026-03-23T03:35:30.009Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"No cloudflared or Tailscale gateway installed. \n\nFor Telegram webhooks, the fundamental requirement is a public HTTPS URL that can reach the gateway. Since Zach's Windows machine is on a consumer ISP behind NAT with no public IP, I need either:\n1. A reverse tunnel service (ngrok, cloudflare tunnel, etc.)\n2. Tailscale with a Funnel or proxy endpoint\n\nLet me think about the most practical approach. Since Tailscale is mentioned in TOOLS.md but the gateway has it disabled, maybe Tailscale is installed but not used by the gateway. Let me check if Tailscale is installed.\n\n\nActually, looking at TAILS.md or checking if Tailscale CLI is available would be the next step. But Tailscale with gateway mode could work—the issue is Tailscale's free tier doesn't include Funnel, and setting up a relay service feels unnecessarily complex. Zach's main concern is reducing Telegram polling overhead, so the real question is whether OpenClaw's Telegram integration supports an efficient webhook approach at all.\n\nFor webhooks to work, OpenClaw needs either its gateway exposed via a public URL or a webhook relay like Webhook relish. Rather than getting stuck on infrastructure, maybe I should check if Zach already has something like a Cloudflare Tunnel running that I could leverage, or if there's another simpler path forward.\n\nSince Tailscale is mentioned in the config but disabled, enabling it could provide the necessary tunnel—if it's installed on the machine, I can check via command line.","thinkingSignature":"d150c5ade4e54f28640313bb9cdc6f6c573ad79ab875b2f7d15c699c1d7d4533"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_blyc2iqv2d1v_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"tailscale status 2>&1"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":21950,"output":342,"cacheRea