{"type":"message","id":"e148f3b9","parentId":"824068bd","timestamp":"2026-03-23T03:38:27.682Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The webhook URL is set to our cloudflare URL (which is shown as empty in the short output but the set call returned success). Wait, it shows `url :` as empty. That's odd. Let me check again...Actually looking at it, `url` appears empty. But `last_synchronization_error_date` is set to a Unix timestamp (1773807500 = March 2026). This is concerning. Let me check if the webhook was actually set properly.Actually wait - the first call returned \"Webhook was set\" with ok=True. But `getWebhookInfo` shows url as empty. This might mean the webhook is now returning empty because cloudflared quick tunnels are temporary - the URL changes each time. \n\nEach time cloudflared starts, it gets a new random URL. So the webhook I just set might already be stale. The empty URL in `getWebhookInfo` is definitely wrong though - the set call succeeded but the URL isn't persisting. That's the real problem here.\n\nI need to either set up a persistent tunnel with Cloudflare (which requires an account and domain) or find another way to keep the webhook URL stable. Since Zach just wants this working without extra setup, I should look at whether there's a local webhook solution or if I can make the cloudflared tunnel persist better.\n\nActually, thinking about this more carefully - the Telegram webhook is currently set to the cloudflare URL, but cloudflared quick tunnels give a new URL each time. The gateway itself doesn't need to be publicly accessible if Telegram is just polling it through the webhook URL. The real issue is whether the webhook will even work with a temporary tunnel URL that changes on restart.\n\nBut if the gateway is already accessible from the internet through cloudflared, and the webhook is configured, then Telegram should be able to reach it. Let me test whether that connection actually works.","thinkingSi