{"type":"message","id":"695d05fa","parentId":"cb473eec","timestamp":"2026-03-23T03:57:48.319Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Zach is asking if there's anything left to do or any improvements to make. Let me think honestly about the personality layer and SPARK bridge.\n\nWhat's done:\n1. SPARK bridge wired in (`hear_spark`, `on_spark`)\n2. Hysteresis decay working\n3. `imaginative` trait wired up\n4. TENSION_TO_SIGNAL map in place\n5. MODE_SIGNALS working\n6. Top-level API functions (`on_message`, `on_spark`, `after_response`, `reset_persona`)\n\nWhat's not done / could be improved:\n\n1. **The personality layer isn't actually called in my response pipeline** — I have the module but it's not integrated into my actual response generation. Right now it's a standalone tool. For it to actually affect how I write, something needs to call `on_message()` when I receive a message and then use the guide when I respond.\n   \n2. **The SPARK hook is unused** — I can call `on_spark()` but there's no trigger anywhere that would invoke it when SPARK-related content comes up.\n\n3. **The `core/personality.py` file is redundant** — `core/persona.py` is the more complete version, so personality.py is probably just legacy code from an earlier version.\n\n4. **The signal weights are guesswork** — 0.35 for signal propagation, 0.1 for resonance, 0.4 for tension signals — none of this has been validated. It's all intuition.\n\n5. **No actual SPARK integration** — I haven't connected this to a real SPARK run yet. The whole point was to have something meaningful to say about the integration, but there's no live link.\n\n6. **The \"guide\" output needs work** — those bullet points with \"activated strongly/somewhat\" feel mechanical. A voice guide should shape how I write, not announce itself.\n\nThe real issue is that this whole thing only matters if it actually changes how I respond. Right now it's just code sitting there.\n\nI should be honest about what would actually make this useful — like integrating `on_message` into the hook system so it fires automatically, or creating a `/spark` command that runs the drift and then calls `on_spark`. But given the time and the fact that the core work is done, the most important thing is that the module itself is solid. The rest is about how you'd want to trigger it.","thinkingSignature":"5d72a5b727c88461c2bb0ef9bf0a820f7c566b7eab27e76ed1a832bee0edebde"},{"type":"text","text":"\nHonestly? The core is solid. What I described earlier is the real situation — the module exists and works, but it's not wired into my actual response generation loop yet. It's a good instrument with no player.\n\nA few honest improvements worth considering:\n\n**1. Actually integrate it** — right now `on_message()` lives in `core/persona.py` but nothing calls it when I receive a message. For it to affect how I write, I'd need to either hook it into the OpenClaw session lifecycle or make it a pre-response step in my own process. The hook system in `hooks/last-session/` could probably do this.\n\n**2. SPARK → personality trigger** — there's no `/spark` command or way to actually invoke SPARK from chat and have the result feed back into my voice. That connection doesn't exist yet. The whole \"SPARK makes Nova more alive\" idea lives in the code but not in any user-facing interface.\n\n**3. `core/personality.py` is now redundant** — it's the older version. `core/persona.py` supersedes it. Should probably consolidate or retire `personality.py`.\n\n**4. The resonance weights are made up** — 0.35, 0.1, 0.4 — none of this is validated. It works in the small but nobody's tested how it actually feels across a real conversation.\n\n**The honest answer:** the foundation is genuinely good. The architecture is right. What's left is the integration work — making it actually fire in my pipeline instead of just sitting there as a callable module.\n\nWant me to wire up option 1 (have `on_message` auto-fire so it actually shapes responses), or would you rather see it in action first through a `/spark` command?"}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":43,"output":862,"cacheRead":13057,"cacheWrite":56229,"totalTokens":70191,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1774238244470}}
{"type":"message","id":"4fc22427","parentId":"695d05fa","timestamp":"2026-03-23T03:58:48.995Z","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Sender (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"label\": \"openclaw-control-ui\",\n  \"id\": \"openclaw-control-ui\"\n}\n```\n\n[Sun 2026-03-22 23:58 EDT] okay go actiuslyy integrate it now and you can do any other mods or changes that you want"}],"timestamp":1774238328988}}
{"type":"message","id":"bf17e689","parentId":"4fc22427","timestamp":"2026-03-23T03:59:14.684Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Zach wants me to actually integrate the personality layer into my response generation loop, and also make any other improvements I want. Let me think about what this means.\n\nThe key question is: how do I actually get `on_message()` called when I receive a message in OpenClaw? Looking at the system prompt, OpenClaw has a hook system (`hooks/last-session/`). But I could also just... call it manually at the start of my response generation. Since I'm an AI assistant responding through OpenClaw, I can simply call `on_message()` as part of my own reasoning process.\n\nActually, looking at the setup more carefully: OpenClaw is my runtime. I'm running inside it. My responses go through the OpenClaw gateway. \n \nI'm realizing there are a few ways to handle this. I could use OpenClaw's hook system to trigger the personality module at session events, or I could just manually invoke it in my response pipeline. The hook system seems cleaner for automation, but since I'm the main agent, I have direct access to my own code and can call the module whenever I want—it's really just about making sure I actually do it.\n\nLooking at the hook options, the session-memory hook might be useful for post-response processing, but really I'm thinking about this differently: I should call `core.persona.on_message()` at the start of each response turn, get the voice guide back, and use that to shape how I write. Since I have direct access to the module in this sandbox, I can just invoke it directly without waiting for external triggers.\n\nThe tricky part is that OpenClaw manages my message flow, so I need to figure out how to hook into that lifecycle. The hook system has options like boot-md for startup and last-session for when sessions end, but there's no built-in hook for the moment before I generate a response. I could potentially use the session-memory hook, but that runs after the session ends rather than during active conversation. Let me think about what actually makes sense here—I'm Zach's AI assistant running inside OpenClaw, so I need to understand how OpenClaw actually processes and routes messages to me so I can find the right integration point. I could modify the hook system to handle message events, but that would require changes to OpenClaw itself. More realistically, since I'm responding as Nova right now, I should just manually invoke `core.persona.on_message()` and `after_response()` in my own response logic. I can add persona state tracking to my memory or context so I know the current emotional register, and then actively use that guide when writing my responses. Now I'm thinking through the specific improvements: calling `on_message()` at the start of my response generation to get the voice guide and use it, adding the `imaginative` trait that SPARK was missing, creating a `/spark` command to trigger SPARK from chat, consolidating the duplicate `personality.py` file, and exploring whether OpenClaw's hook system can be extended to handle message events.\n\nFor the actual implementation, I'd add code at the beginning of my response function to invoke `on_message()` with the user's message, retrieve the voice guide, and then use that to shape my response before calling `after_response()` to update the state. The tricky part is that I'm responding through OpenClaw, so I'd need to either modify how the main agent processes messages or find a hook point in OpenClaw's system. The most practical approach might be checking if OpenClaw supports a `HOOK.md` file in the hooks directory that could handle message interception.\n\nActually, I'm realizing the session hooks run at specific times—when a session starts or ends—but there's no built-in hook for the moment a message arrives. Rather than trying to force OpenClaw to do something it doesn't support, I could just directly modify the agent logic itself. I have access to `AGENTS.md`, which is my workspace configuration, so I can add persona invocation there as a pre-response step. I could even create a dedicated hook in `hooks/on-message/` that runs before each response. Since I'm the main agent, I can simply start invoking the persona module at the appropriate points in my own code. I think the simplest path forward is to add persona calls directly to my response flow in AGENTS.md, create a Spark command handler in the hooks directory, and consolidate the personality.py files. For OpenClaw specifically, I should check what hook points are available and whether there's a way to run code before each response. I'm realizing the cleanest approach is to add persona state tracking to my existing context files and invoke it before each response. Let me start by creating an `on-message` hook directory with a handler that processes the persona state, then check how OpenClaw's hook system actually works.","thinkingSignature":"d5daf2795082de92323361e6286aa6312584b40e4dc3f86de7263a9e424b3f72"},{"type":"text","text":"Let me first understand the hook system, then build this properly.\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_hagrmvvq202x_1","name":"read","arguments":{"path":"C:\\Users\\Zwmar\\.openclaw\\workspace\\hooks\\last-session\\HOOK.md"}},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_hagrmvvq202x_2","name":"read","arguments":{"path":"C:\\Users\\Zwmar\\.openclaw\\workspace\\hooks\\last-session\\handler.js"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":0,"output":1074,"cacheRead":69767,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":70841,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1774238328992}}
{"type":"message","id":"2c2e61ea","parentId":"bf17e689","timestamp":"2026-03-23T03:59:14.713Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_hagrmvvq202x_1","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"---\nname: last-session\ndescription: \"Saves the previous session's transcript to LAST_SESSION.md when /new is issued, enabling zero-beat context resume\"\nhomepage: https://docs.openclaw.ai/automation/hooks#last-session\nmetadata:\n  {\n    \"openclaw\": {\n      \"emoji\": \"🔄\",\n      \"events\": [\"command:new\"],\n      \"requires\": { \"config\": [\"workspace.dir\"] }\n    }\n  }\n---\n\n# Last Session Hook\n\nWhen `/new` is issued, saves the previous session's full transcript to `memory/LAST_SESSION.md` so the next session can resume without missing a beat.\n\n## What It Does\n\n1. Fires on `command:new`\n2. Locates the previous session's transcript (via `context.previousSessionEntry` or fallback search)\n3. Extracts all user/assistant messages\n4. Writes them to `memory/LAST_SESSION.md` with session metadata header\n5. The session startup sequence reads this file and injects its contents\n\n## Output Format\n\n```markdown\n# LAST SESSION (Session ID: abc123)\n**DO NOT clear or delete this file until the new session has started.**\n\n## Previous Session Context\n\n[full transcript of previous conversation]\n\n---\n```\n\nThe startup sequence reads this file and injects the transcript into the new session's context.\n"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1774238354706}}
{"type":"message","id":"9a5e7e38","parentId":"2c2e61ea","timestamp":"2026-03-23T03:59:14.722Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_hagrmvvq202x_2","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"import fs from \"node:fs/promises\";\nimport os from \"node:os\";\nimport path from \"node:path\";\nimport { writeFileWithinRoot } from \"../../query-expansion-DnS6CGY2.js\";\nimport { createSubsystemLogger } from \"../../subsystem-CDcEQtQK.js\";\nimport { parseAgentSessionKey } from \"../../workspace-Cg3kGb1y.js\";\nimport { hasInterSessionUserProvenance } from \"../../model-selection-CU2b7bN6.js\";\nimport { resolveHookConfig } from \"../../config-BYkzFD4a.js\";\n\nconst log = createSubsystemLogger(\"hooks/last-session\");\n\n/**\n * Read all user/assistant messages from a JSONL transcript file\n */\nasync function getSessionTranscript(sessionFilePath) {\n  try {\n    const content = await fs.readFile(sessionFilePath, \"utf-8\");\n    const lines = content.trim().split(\"\\n\");\n    const messages = [];\n\n    for (const line of lines) {\n      try {\n        const entry = JSON.parse(line);\n        if (entry.type !== \"message\" || !entry.message) continue;\n\n        const msg = entry.message;\n        const role = msg.role;\n\n        // Skip inter-session user messages\n        if (role === \"user\" && hasInterSessionUserProvenance(msg)) continue;\n\n        if ((role === \"user\" || role === \"assistant\") && msg.content) {\n          // Handle content as array (with text parts) or string\n          const text = Array.isArray(msg.content)\n            ? msg.content.find((c) => c.type === \"text\")?.text\n            : typeof msg.content === \"string\"\n              ? msg.content\n              : null;\n\n          if (text && !text.startsWith(\"/\")) {\n            messages.push({ role, text });\n          }\n        }\n      } catch {\n        // Skip malformed lines\n      }\n    }\n\n    return messages;\n  } catch {\n    return null;\n  }\n}\n\n/**\n * Try to find the previous session file using the same logic as session-memory\n */\nasync function findPreviousSessionFile(sessionsDir, currentSessionFile, sessionId) {\n  try {\n    const files = await fs.readdir(sessionsDir);\n    const fileSet = new Set(files);\n\n    // Try: sessionId.jsonl\n    if (sessionId) {\n      const canonical = `${sessionId}.jsonl`;\n      if (fileSet.has(canonical)) return path.join(sessionsDir, canonical);\n\n      // Topic variants\n      const topicVariants = files\n        .filter((n) => n.startsWith(`${sessionId}-topic-`) && n.endsWith(\".jsonl\") && !n.includes(\".reset.\"))\n        .toSorted()\n        .toReversed();\n      if (topicVariants.length > 0) return path.join(sessionsDir, topicVariants[0]);\n    }\n\n    // Try: strip .reset. suffix from current file and find canonical\n    if (currentSessionFile) {\n      const baseName = path.basename(currentSessionFile);\n      const resetIdx = baseName.indexOf(\".reset.\");\n      if (resetIdx !== -1) {\n        const stripped = baseName.slice(0, resetIdx);\n        if (fileSet.has(stripped)) return path.join(sessionsDir, stripped);\n      }\n    }\n\n    // Fallback: most recent non-reset jsonl\n    const candidates = files\n      .filter((n) => n.endsWith(\".jsonl\") && !n.includes(\".reset.\"))\n      .toSorted()\n      .toReversed();\n    return candidates.length > 0 ? path.join(sessionsDir, candidates[0]) : null;\n  } catch {\n    return null;\n  }\n}\n\nconst handler = async (event) => {\n  if (event.type !== \"command\" || (event.action !== \"new\" && event.action !== \"reset\")) return;\n\n  try {\n    const ctx = event.context || {};\n    const cfg = ctx.cfg;\n    const workspaceDir = ctx.workspaceDir || null;\n\n    // Get the PREVIOUS session (before reset)\n    const prevEntry = ctx.previousSessionEntry || ctx.sessionEntry || {};\n    const prevSessionId = prevEntry.sessionId;\n    let prevSessionFile = prevEntry.sessionFile || null;\n\n    // If session file is missing or is a reset file, try to recover\n    if (!prevSessionFile || prevSessionFile.includes(\".reset.\")) {\n      const sessionsDirs = new Set();\n      if (prevSessionFile) sessionsDirs.add(path.dirname(prevSessionFile));\n      if (workspaceDir) sessionsDirs.add(path.join(workspaceDir, \"sessions\"));\n\n      for (const sd of sessionsDirs) {\n        const recovered = await findPreviousSessionFile(sd, prevSessionFile, prevSessionId);\n        if (recovered) {\n          prevSessionFile = recovered;\n          break;\n        }\n      }\n    }\n\n    if (!prevSessionFile) {\n      log.debug(\"No previous session file found, skipping\");\n      return;\n    }\n\n    // Read transcript\n    const messages = await getSessionTranscript(prevSessionFile);\n    if (!messages || messages.length === 0) {\n      log.debug(\"No messages found in previous session, skipping\");\n      return;\n    }\n\n    // Format transcript for injection\n    const transcriptLines = messages.map((m) => {\n      const prefix = m.role === \"user\" ? \"**You**\" : \"**Nova**\";\n      return `${prefix}: ${m.text}`;\n    });\n\n    const now = new Date(event.timestamp);\n    const dateStr = now.toISOString().split(\"T\")[0];\n    const timeStr = now.toISOString().split(\"T\")[1].split(\".\")[0];\n    const slug = `${dateStr}-${timeStr}`;\n\n    const content = [\n      `# LAST SESSION (${prevSessionId || \"unknown\"})`,\n      `**Saved at:** ${dateStr} ${timeStr} UTC`,\n      `**Source:** ${ctx.commandSource || \"unknown\"}`,\n      \"\",\n      \"---\",\n      \"**CONTEXT INJECTION — DO NOT CLEAR THIS FILE**\",\n      \"The session below ended when /new was issued. Its context is automatically\",\n      \"injected into this session so Nova can resume without missing a beat.\",\n      \"---\",\n      \"\",\n      \"## Transcript\",\n      \"\",\n      ...transcriptLines,\n      \"\",\n      `---`,\n      `*Session saved by last-session hook at ${now.toISOString()}*`,\n    ].join(\"\\n\");\n\n    const memoryDir = path.join(workspaceDir, \"memory\");\n    const memoryFilePath = path.join(memoryDir, \"LAST_SESSION.md\");\n\n    await fs.mkdir(memoryDir, { recursive: true });\n    await writeFileWithinRoot({\n      rootDir: memoryDir,\n      relativePath: \"LAST_SESSION.md\",\n      data: content,\n      encoding: \"utf-8\",\n    });\n\n    log.info(`Previous session saved to memory/LAST_SESSION.md (${messages.length} messages)`);\n  } catch (err) {\n    if (err instanceof Error) {\n      log.error(\"last-session hook failed\", { name: err.name, message: err.message });\n    } else {\n      log.error(\"last-session hook failed\", { error: String(err) });\n    }\n  }\n};\n\nexport default handler;\n"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1774238354713}}
{"type":"message","id":"f854c9a4","parentId":"9a5e7e38","timestamp":"2026-03-23T03:59:28.675Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I understand the hook system. Hooks are JavaScript files that export a handler. They're triggered by events like `command:new`, `session:start`, etc.\n\nLooking at the HOOK.md for last-session, the events are `[\"command:new\"]`. This is a command event.\n\nFor an `on-message` hook, I need to understand what events are available. Let me check the OpenClaw docs on hooks to understand what event types exist.\n\nBut since I can't access the docs right now easily, let me think about this differently. The hook system reacts to events. What I want is to:\n1. Have `on_message()` called when the user sends a message, BEFORE I generate a response\n\n\n2. Have `after_response()` called AFTER I send a response\n\nThe problem is there might not be a \"before response\" event exposed. Let me look at what the OpenClaw docs say about available hook events, or maybe I can find a `session:end` event that fires after a response is sent, though that would be after the turn completes rather than before.\n\nActually, I think the simplest approach is to just call `on_message()` at the start of each of my response turns and use the voice guide it returns. Since I'm writing the response myself, I can incorporate that guidance directly into what I write, then call `after_response()` when I'm done. This doesn't require modifying OpenClaw itself or creating new hooks—it's just me using the tools I already have available in the session.\n\nSo my plan is to create a hook that fires on message events to call `on_message()` and store the voice guide somewhere I can reference, then use that guide to shape my response. Let me check what hook events are actually available in OpenClaw first.","thinkingSignature":"3e4356b5c1fffc775594f683b36413d5b83f4d928eb1d9c1777b7b98aecda5d3"},{"type":"text","text":"Let me check what events the hook system supports before building.\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_c49j1mzp7pzg_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"Get-ChildItem \"C:\\Users\\Zwmar\\AppData\\Roaming\\npm\\node_modules\\openclaw\\docs\" -Recurse -File | Where-Object { $_.Name -match \"hook\" } | Select-Object FullName"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":59598,"output":449,"cacheRead":13057,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":73104,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1774238354724}}
